Technological determinism is a term that in practice implies a wide range of ideas, from the technological instinct or technological imperative to the strict sense that the fate of man is guided by the basic logic associated with the laws of science and their representation in technology. ...
Two general ideas are common to most interpretations of technological determinism: that the development of technology itself follows a path that is far beyond the influence of cultural or political, and that the technology of technology in turn has an "influence" on society that is inherent, not social.
For example, someone may say that a motor vehicle necessarily leads to the development of a roadway.
However, a nationwide road network is not economically viable for just a few cars, which is why new production methods have been developed to reduce the cost of owning a car.
Mass ownership of the car also leads to an increase in road accidents, leading to the discovery of new health techniques for repair of injured bodies.
